  "text": "In this work, we further investigate the complexity of the bribery problem in the setting of voting with CP-nets as initiated by Mattei et al. [CITATION_1] . The difference to the 'classical' setting where preferences are given as linear orders is that the briber does not directly execute changes in the preference orders of the voters, but in the CP-nets, i.e., he can affect the dependencies. From the point of view of campaign management, this seems very natural as well. One can easily imagine a systematic campaign to convince voters to drop dependencies in their preferences, without having to deal with their implicit preference order. For instance, if a voter prefers some special kind of wine in the case that meat is served as a main dish, one might run a campaign for the quality of the alternative varieties of wine offered and therewith directly affect the CP-net, without having to care about the induced preference order.",
